{"domain_analysis":{"business_context":"New 'Express Delivery' product offering time-sensitive courier service with a target 2-hour delivery window, premium pricing, and a refund policy for missed windows. Synthesized from raw product discovery workshop notes involving PM, Operations, Finance, Customer Success, and Legal stakeholders.","bounded_context":"Express Delivery — a sub-domain of Order Fulfillment that governs express-tier eligibility, dispatch, SLA tracking, and express-specific refund policy.","ubiquitous_language":[{"term":"Express Delivery","definition":"A premium delivery tier with a target 2-hour delivery window from order placement, available to customers within 10km of a warehouse."},{"term":"Express Fee","definition":"A $12.99 surcharge applied on top of the base delivery fee for express-tier service."},{"term":"Base Delivery Fee","definition":"The standard delivery charge that applies to all orders regardless of tier. Not refundable under the express SLA miss policy."},{"term":"Express Window","definition":"The 2-hour period from order placement within which the delivery should be completed. NOTE: disputed whether this is a guarantee or best-effort target (see escalations)."},{"term":"Pickup SLA","definition":"The 15-minute window from order placement within which a driver must pick up the express order from the warehouse."},{"term":"Express-Eligible Customer","definition":"A customer whose delivery address is within 10km of an active warehouse."},{"term":"Express-Qualified Driver","definition":"A driver with a rating of 4.0 stars or above, eligible to fulfill express orders."},{"term":"SLA Miss","definition":"When an express delivery is not completed within the express window, triggering the refund policy (subject to exclusions)."},{"term":"Driver Cancellation Replacement Window","definition":"The 10-minute window within which a replacement driver must be assigned after a mid-delivery driver cancellation, before an automatic refund is triggered."},{"term":"Goodwill Refund","definition":"Legal's characterization of the express fee refund — a voluntary gesture, not a contractual obligation."},{"term":"Wrong Address Exclusion","definition":"A refund exclusion where the SLA miss was caused by the customer providing an incorrect delivery address."}]},"business_rules":[{"id":"BR-1","rule":"Express delivery is only available to customers whose delivery address is within 10km of an active warehouse.","invariant":true,"invariant_justification":"Physical constraint — the 2-hour window is impossible to meet beyond this radius given operational logistics. Allowing orders outside this radius corrupts the service promise.","testable_assertion":"Given a delivery address >10km from the nearest warehouse, the system MUST NOT allow express tier selection."},{"id":"BR-2","rule":"The express fee is $12.99, charged on top of the base delivery fee.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"Pricing is a business policy that can be changed by commercial leadership.","testable_assertion":"Given an express order, the order total includes a line item of $12.99 labeled as the express fee, in addition to the base delivery fee."},{"id":"BR-3","rule":"An express order must be picked up by a driver within 15 minutes of order placement.","invariant":true,"invariant_justification":"Operational constraint that directly governs whether the 2-hour window is achievable. Violating this makes downstream SLA compliance physically impossible.","testable_assertion":"Given an express order not picked up within 15 minutes, the system flags an internal SLA breach on the pickup stage."},{"id":"BR-4","rule":"Only drivers with a rating of 4.0 stars or above may be assigned to express orders.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"Quality threshold is a business policy. Operations could adjust this threshold based on driver supply.","testable_assertion":"Given a driver with a rating below 4.0, the dispatch system MUST NOT assign them to an express order."},{"id":"BR-5","rule":"When the express window is missed and the miss is not caused by a wrong customer address, the express fee (not the base delivery fee) is refunded.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"Refund policy is a business decision that can be modified by Finance/Legal.","testable_assertion":"Given an SLA miss where the customer address was correct, a refund of exactly $12.99 (the express fee) is issued. The base delivery fee is NOT refunded."},{"id":"BR-6","rule":"No express fee refund is issued if the SLA miss was caused by the customer providing a wrong address.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"Refund exclusion policy, modifiable by business.","testable_assertion":"Given an SLA miss where the delivery address was flagged as incorrect by the driver, no express fee refund is issued."},{"id":"BR-7","rule":"Express fee refunds are processed within 3 business days.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"Processing timeline is an operational policy.","testable_assertion":"Given an approved express refund, the refund transaction is initiated within 3 business days of the SLA miss event."},{"id":"BR-8","rule":"If a driver cancels mid-delivery on an express order, a replacement driver must be assigned within 10 minutes. If no replacement is assigned within 10 minutes, the express fee is automatically refunded.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"Replacement window and auto-refund are operational policies.","testable_assertion":"Given a driver cancellation on an active express delivery, if 10 minutes elapse with no replacement assigned, the system automatically triggers an express fee refund."},{"id":"BR-9","rule":"Express customers can track their assigned driver's location in real time.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"Feature requirement, not a data integrity constraint.","testable_assertion":"Given an active express delivery with an assigned driver, the customer-facing app displays the driver's current location, updating at least every 30 seconds."},{"id":"BR-10","rule":"The express delivery window (2-hour target) must be prominently displayed to the customer at order placement and during tracking.","invariant":false,"invariant_justification":"UX requirement, not a system invariant.","testable_assertion":"Given an express order, the estimated delivery time showing the 2-hour window is visible on the order confirmation screen and the live tracking screen."}],"acceptance_criteria":[],"edge_cases":[{"scenario":"Customer is exactly 10km from a warehouse","expected_behavior":"AMBIGUOUS — need to clarify whether 10km is inclusive (<=10km) or exclusive (<10km). Recommend inclusive (<=10km)."},{"scenario":"Driver rating drops below 4.0 mid-delivery","expected_behavior":"The driver should complete the current delivery (cannot reassign mid-transit without disruption). The rating gate applies at assignment time, not during delivery."},{"scenario":"No express-qualified drivers available within 15-minute pickup window","expected_behavior":"The pickup SLA is breached internally. The system should alert operations. The order proceeds but is flagged as at-risk for SLA miss. OPEN QUESTION: should the customer be notified proactively?"},{"scenario":"Customer provides a wrong address, then corrects it, but the correction causes the SLA miss","expected_behavior":"AMBIGUOUS — was the SLA miss caused by the wrong address? Need policy on whether address correction resets the clock or if the original wrong address is still the root cause."},{"scenario":"Driver cancels at minute 109 of the 2-hour window","expected_behavior":"Replacement window of 10 minutes would extend past the 2-hour mark. Both the SLA miss refund and the replacement failure refund could trigger. Refund should only be issued once (deduplicated)."},{"scenario":"Multiple driver cancellations on the same express order","expected_behavior":"Each cancellation restarts the 10-minute replacement window. If total elapsed time exceeds 2 hours, the SLA miss refund triggers regardless. Only one refund of $12.99 is issued total."},{"scenario":"Customer address is within 10km of warehouse A but warehouse A has no stock; nearest stocked warehouse B is >10km away","expected_behavior":"AMBIGUOUS — is eligibility based on proximity to ANY warehouse or only to a warehouse that can fulfill the order? This is a critical gap."},{"scenario":"System clock discrepancy between order placement and delivery completion timestamps","expected_behavior":"SLA measurement must use a single authoritative time source (server-side UTC). Client-side timestamps must not be used for SLA calculations."},{"scenario":"Express order placed 1 minute before warehouse closing time","expected_behavior":"AMBIGUOUS — need policy on express order cutoff times relative to warehouse operating hours."}],"business_impact":{"financial":"Express fee ($12.99) creates a new premium revenue stream. Refund liability from SLA misses is a direct cost — if miss rates exceed ~15-20%, the product may be margin-negative. The 3-business-day refund processing window helps cash flow but may frustrate customers expecting instant refunds (especially given the 'automatic refund' language from Customer Success).","operational":"15-minute pickup SLA creates significant dispatch pressure — requires dedicated express driver pool or priority queue in dispatch. 4-star driver rating requirement constrains the eligible driver pool. 10-minute replacement window for cancellations requires real-time dispatch monitoring and standby capacity. Real-time tracking requires GPS infrastructure investment.","user":"Prominent 2-hour window display sets strong customer expectations. The legal/PM contradiction on 'guarantee' vs 'best effort' MUST be resolved before launch — if customers see 'guaranteed' but terms say 'best effort', trust is destroyed on first miss. Real-time tracking is a strong differentiator but sets high reliability expectations.","risk":"HIGH RISK: The guarantee vs best-effort contradiction exposes the company to false advertising claims if the PM's language is used in marketing but Legal's position governs the terms of service. MEDIUM RISK: 'Wrong address' exclusion lacks clear definition — who determines the address was wrong? Driver's word vs customer's word creates dispute risk. MEDIUM RISK: No definition of what constitutes a 'miss' — is it delivery to door, or delivery completed in app?","stakeholders_affected":[{"group":"Customers","impact":"Premium service with time commitment. Risk of expectation mismatch between marketing language and legal terms. Real-time tracking improves experience."},{"group":"Drivers","impact":"Higher performance bar (4-star minimum). Tighter time pressure (15-min pickup). May need express-specific incentives to maintain supply."},{"group":"Warehouse Operations","impact":"Must support 15-minute pickup readiness. Express orders likely need priority picking/packing. May need dedicated express staging area."},{"group":"Finance","impact":"New revenue line. Refund processing within 3 business days. Need to track SLA miss rates for margin analysis."},{"group":"Customer Support","impact":"Will handle disputes on 'wrong address' exclusions. Need clear escalation paths. 'Automatic refund' for replacement failure reduces ticket volume but 3-day processing may generate 'where is my refund' inquiries."},{"group":"Legal/Compliance","impact":"Must resolve guarantee vs best-effort language before any customer-facing communication. Refund policy terms must be explicit in T&Cs."},{"group":"Engineering","impact":"Real-time tracking infrastructure. SLA timer implementation. Automated refund triggers. Geofencing for 10km eligibility."}]},"confidence":{"level":35,"reasoning":"Confidence is very low because the spec contains a fundamental unresolved contradiction between PM ('guaranteed') and Legal ('best effort / goodwill only') that affects the core product promise, refund obligations, and all customer-facing language. Additionally, Customer Success describes 'automatic' refunds while Finance describes a 3-business-day processing window — the trigger mechanism and timing are unclear. Multiple critical gaps remain (wrong address determination, SLA miss definition, warehouse eligibility). Acceptance criteria cannot be written until the guarantee vs best-effort contradiction is resolved.","high_confidence_areas":["Express fee amount ($12.99)","10km eligibility radius requirement","15-minute pickup SLA","4-star driver rating minimum","Base delivery fee is not refunded on SLA miss"],"low_confidence_areas":["Whether the 2-hour window is a guarantee or best-effort target","Whether refunds are automatic or require processing time","How 'wrong address' is determined and by whom","What exactly constitutes delivery completion for SLA measurement","Whether eligibility is warehouse proximity or fulfillable warehouse proximity"],"assumptions":["The 10km radius is calculated as straight-line distance, not driving distance","Driver rating is a cumulative average, not a rolling window","The 2-hour window starts at order placement, not at pickup","Only one express fee refund is issued per order regardless of how many refund triggers fire"]},"escalations":[{"type":"contradiction","description":"PM states the 2-hour delivery is 'guaranteed' and the refund is the remedy for a missed guarantee. Legal explicitly states this CANNOT be a guarantee — it is 'best effort' and the refund is a 'goodwill gesture, not legally enforceable.' This is a fundamental contradiction that affects the entire product positioning, customer-facing language, refund policy enforceability, and potential false advertising exposure. The product cannot launch until this is resolved.","affected_stakeholders":["Customers","Legal/Compliance","Product Management","Marketing","Customer Support"],"options":["A) Use 'guarantee' language with legally binding refund obligation (PM's position — higher customer trust, higher legal exposure)","B) Use 'best effort target' language with discretionary goodwill refund (Legal's position — lower risk, weaker value proposition)","C) Use 'guarantee' in marketing but define it narrowly in T&Cs with specific exclusions (compromise — requires careful legal drafting)"],"recommendation":"Option C as a pragmatic middle ground, but this MUST be reviewed and approved by Legal before any implementation begins. The refund policy should be codified in T&Cs with explicit exclusions rather than left as informal goodwill."},{"type":"contradiction","description":"Customer Success says refunds should happen 'automatically' when a replacement driver is not assigned within 10 minutes. Finance says refunds are 'processed within 3 business days.' These are contradictory — is the refund triggered automatically by the system in real-time, or does it enter a manual processing queue? The word 'automatic' implies instant system-triggered action; '3 business days' implies a batch or manual process.","affected_stakeholders":["Customers","Finance","Customer Support","Engineering"],"options":["A) Fully automatic: system triggers refund instantly when 10-minute window expires (Customer Success position)","B) Auto-approved but batch-processed: system approves the refund immediately but financial processing takes up to 3 business days (compromise)","C) Manual review queue: all refunds go through Finance review within 3 business days (Finance position)"],"recommendation":"Option B — the refund is auto-approved by the system (no human decision needed) but the actual credit to the customer's payment method takes up to 3 business days due to payment processing realities. This satisfies both stakeholders."},{"type":"ambiguity","description":"'Wrong address' as a refund exclusion is undefined. There is no specification for: (1) Who determines the address is wrong — the driver, the system, or customer support? (2) What constitutes 'wrong' — typo, unreachable location, gated community without access code, apartment number missing? (3) What evidence is required? (4) Can the customer dispute the determination? Without clear rules, this becomes a source of customer disputes and inconsistent support decisions.","affected_stakeholders":["Customers","Customer Support","Drivers","Legal/Compliance"],"options":["A) Driver reports wrong address via app with photo evidence; customer can dispute through support","B) System detects address anomalies (geocoding failure, known bad addresses) pre-order","C) Any address correction after order placement counts as 'wrong address'"],"recommendation":"Combine A and B — use geocoding validation at order time to catch obvious errors, and allow driver-reported wrong addresses with photo evidence. Customer must have a dispute path. Define 'wrong address' explicitly in T&Cs."},{"type":"missing_context","description":"No definition of when the 2-hour SLA clock stops. Is delivery 'complete' when: (a) the driver arrives at the address, (b) the package is handed to the customer, (c) the driver marks delivery complete in the app, or (d) the customer confirms receipt? Each definition produces different SLA outcomes and dispute scenarios.","affected_stakeholders":["Customers","Drivers","Operations","Engineering"],"options":["A) Driver arrives at delivery address (GPS geofence)","B) Driver marks 'delivered' in app","C) Customer confirms receipt","D) Package scanned at delivery point"],"recommendation":"Option B with GPS validation — driver marks complete AND must be within geofence of delivery address. This prevents premature completion marking while not depending on customer action (which could be delayed)."}],"rejection_reasons":[{"violation":"Cannot define acceptance criteria due to unresolved guarantee vs best-effort contradiction","business_rule_broken":"The core product promise is undefined — every downstream rule about refunds, customer communication, and SLA enforcement depends on resolving this fundamental question first."}]}
